00:00:28.700 --> 00:00:31.870
Let’s get started.

00:00:31.870 --> 00:00:35.620
This second lesson is about interfaces and
cables.

00:00:35.620 --> 00:00:40.800
In the last video we talked about some different
kinds of devices you will find in networks.

00:00:40.800 --> 00:00:47.239
This lesson will focus on how we connect them,
specifically how we connect them with cables.

00:00:47.239 --> 00:00:53.440
Wireless connections are also a topic we’ll
cover, but that’s for later in the course.

00:00:53.440 --> 00:00:55.290
Take a look at this photo.

00:00:55.290 --> 00:00:58.180
This is the front of a switch.

00:00:58.180 --> 00:01:02.120
Notice the 24 interfaces, also known as ports.

00:01:02.120 --> 00:01:07.080
Remember, as we learned in the last lecture,
one characteristic of switches is that they

00:01:07.080 --> 00:01:12.800
tend to have lots of interfaces to connect
end hosts like PCs and servers to.

00:01:12.800 --> 00:01:15.770
Now let’s look at that those words above
the interfaces.

00:01:15.770 --> 00:01:19.820
I’ll zoom in.

00:01:19.820 --> 00:01:25.450
10/100/100Base-T ports (1 – 24) – Ports
are Auto-MDIX.

00:01:25.450 --> 00:01:31.600
Unless you’ve already studied this stuff,
you probably have no idea what that means.

00:01:31.600 --> 00:01:38.720
Don’t worry, by the end of this video you’ll
understand all of this and more.

00:01:38.720 --> 00:01:41.000
Now let’s focus on the interfaces themselves.

00:01:41.000 --> 00:01:44.170
I’ll zoom in again.

00:01:44.170 --> 00:01:46.250
Do you recognize this shape?

00:01:46.250 --> 00:01:51.260
If your computer is connected to a wired network,
it’s surely using a port like this to connect

00:01:51.260 --> 00:01:53.450
to the network.

00:01:53.450 --> 00:01:56.280
These are called RJ-45 ports.

00:01:56.280 --> 00:01:59.939
RJ stands for Registered Jack, by the way.

00:01:59.939 --> 00:02:06.700
Let’s look at the RJ-45 connector at the
end of a cable, I’m sure you’ve seen one

00:02:06.700 --> 00:02:07.700
before.

00:02:07.700 --> 00:02:11.390
These are all cables with RJ-45 connectors.

00:02:11.390 --> 00:02:16.109
As you can see there are some variations in
design and color, but all of these connectors

00:02:16.109 --> 00:02:20.500
would fit into the ports we saw in the previous
slide.

00:02:20.500 --> 00:02:26.349
The RJ-45 connector is used on the end of
a copper Ethernet cable.

00:02:26.349 --> 00:02:30.269
There are Ethernet cables which do not use
copper wiring as well, but we’ll get to

00:02:30.269 --> 00:02:32.230
that later.

00:02:32.230 --> 00:02:37.219
First of all though, what is Ethernet?

00:02:37.219 --> 00:02:43.540
Ethernet is a collection of network protocols and standards,
rather than just a single protocol.

00:02:43.540 --> 00:02:48.459
So really Ethernet isn’t one single thing,
making it difficult to define exactly what

00:02:48.459 --> 00:02:50.750
it is.

00:02:50.750 --> 00:02:55.459
For the purpose of this lesson, we will focus
on types of cabling as defined by Ethernet

00:02:55.459 --> 00:02:57.889
standards.

00:02:57.889 --> 00:03:02.480
As said above there are many standards included
in Ethernet, but the focus of this lesson

00:03:02.480 --> 00:03:07.029
is interfaces and cables, so that’s what
we’ll focus on.

00:03:07.029 --> 00:03:11.589
However, we will learn other aspects of Ethernet
in future lessons.

00:03:11.589 --> 00:03:16.760
Now, before we learn about Ethernet cable
standards, I want to give a brief explanation

00:03:16.760 --> 00:03:21.370
of why we need network protocols and standards.

00:03:21.370 --> 00:03:26.359
If two people are talking to each other, and
one only speaks English, and the other only

00:03:26.359 --> 00:03:32.659
speaks Japanese, there’s not going to be
a much, or any, communication between them.

00:03:32.659 --> 00:03:37.469
What they need is some agreed upon system
of communicating, like a common language between

00:03:37.469 --> 00:03:39.519
them.

00:03:39.519 --> 00:03:42.599
Network protocols serve that purpose for network
devices.

00:03:42.599 --> 00:03:47.669
That’s why standards like Ethernet exist.

00:03:47.669 --> 00:03:52.639
Since we’re talking about interfaces and
cables in this video, here’s a more relevant

00:03:52.639 --> 00:03:54.139
example.

00:03:54.139 --> 00:03:59.979
If you’re trying to connect to, for example,
a network switch, but the maker of the cable

00:03:59.979 --> 00:04:04.290
and the maker of the switch haven’t agreed
upon the size and shape of the connector and

00:04:04.290 --> 00:04:07.079
port, you won’t be able to connect them.

00:04:07.079 --> 00:04:12.129
That’s why there are industry standards
that all vendors follow, both in terms of

00:04:12.129 --> 00:04:16.970
physical standards like connectors and cables
like these, as well as logical standards,

00:04:16.970 --> 00:04:20.669
like IP, the internet protocol.

00:04:20.669 --> 00:04:27.180
Now, connections between devices in a network
operate at a set speed.

00:04:27.180 --> 00:04:30.560
These speeds are measured in bits per second.

00:04:30.560 --> 00:04:32.009
What is a bit?

00:04:32.009 --> 00:04:37.730
Well it’s a value represented by either
a 0 or a 1.

00:04:37.730 --> 00:04:40.990
This binary code is how computers work.

00:04:40.990 --> 00:04:48.281
YouTube, this video, your operating system,
all of it just a series of 0s and 1s which

00:04:48.281 --> 00:04:51.150
your computer interprets.

00:04:51.150 --> 00:04:56.240
When communicating across a copper network
cable, a variation in the electrical signal

00:04:56.240 --> 00:05:00.080
is interpreted by the receiving device as
a 0 or a 1.

00:05:00.080 --> 00:05:02.940
So, that’s a bit, what’s a byte?

00:05:02.949 --> 00:05:09.400
Here we have a series of 8 bits.

00:05:09.400 --> 00:05:13.930
8 bits is equal to 1 byte.

00:05:13.930 --> 00:05:17.629
Now, speed is measured in bits per second.

00:05:17.629 --> 00:05:23.819
Imagine a byte, 8 bits, of data being sent along a 
wire.

00:05:23.880 --> 00:05:28.320
It reaches the neighboring device one bit
at a time like this.

00:05:28.320 --> 00:05:31.960
It doesn’t operate one byte at a time like
this.

00:05:31.960 --> 00:05:39.639
So, remember, speed is measured in bits per
second, for example kilobits per second, megabits

00:05:39.639 --> 00:05:45.810
per second, gigabits per second, and not bytes
per second.

00:05:45.810 --> 00:05:51.189
Data on a hard drive for example is measured
in bytes, however, so remember a Gigabyte

00:05:51.189 --> 00:05:55.979
is actually 8 times larger than a gigabit.

00:05:55.979 --> 00:05:58.629
So let’s review some of these measurements.

00:05:58.629 --> 00:06:02.789
1 kilobit is equal to 1,000 bits.

00:06:02.789 --> 00:06:05.550
Add three zeroes to that

00:06:05.550 --> 00:06:09.050
And you get 1 megabit, which is 1 million
bits.

00:06:09.050 --> 00:06:11.680
Add another three zeroes,

00:06:11.680 --> 00:06:15.749
And you get one gigabit, or 1 billion bits.

00:06:15.749 --> 00:06:18.219
Add another three zeroes to that

00:06:18.219 --> 00:06:21.800
and you get one terabit, 1 trillion bits.

00:06:21.800 --> 00:06:27.590
You’re not going to see larger units than
this when it comes to network speed, and really

00:06:27.590 --> 00:06:30.590
you’re not going to see terabits either.

00:06:30.590 --> 00:06:34.449
Speeds are always increasing, however, so
terabits-per-second speeds may be commonplace

00:06:34.449 --> 00:06:35.690
soon enough!

00:06:35.690 --> 00:06:41.849
Now, there are further units, here’s a snapshot
from wikipedia.

00:06:41.849 --> 00:06:47.289
Beyond terabits there are petabits, exabits,
zettabits, yottabits, and more.

00:06:47.289 --> 00:06:50.870
Don’t worry about memorizing all of these
though, you’re not going to see network

00:06:50.870 --> 00:06:54.080
speeds like these anytime soon!

00:06:54.080 --> 00:06:58.710
Okay, finally lets talk about some Ethernet
standards.

00:06:58.710 --> 00:07:04.330
These are all defined in the IEEE 802.3 standard.

00:07:04.330 --> 00:07:09.430
The IEEE is the institute of electrical and
electronics engineers.

00:07:09.430 --> 00:07:15.189
You’ll notice all of these Ethernet standards
begin with IEEE 802.3.

00:07:15.189 --> 00:07:17.379
Let’s take a look.

00:07:17.379 --> 00:07:24.069
So, here’s a table of some IEEE standards
for copper Ethernet cables.

00:07:24.069 --> 00:07:29.659
We’ll also take a look at fiber optic cables
later in this lesson, but I decided to split

00:07:29.659 --> 00:07:32.219
them up.

00:07:32.219 --> 00:07:37.710
We have one for each of the common network
cable speeds, 10 megabits per second, 100

00:07:37.710 --> 00:07:44.210
megabits per second, 1 gigabit per second,
and 10 gigabits per second.

00:07:44.210 --> 00:07:47.169
The next column lists the common names.

00:07:47.169 --> 00:07:52.100
These are the names we usually use when talking
about different networks interfaces, cables,

00:07:52.100 --> 00:07:56.330
and their speeds, for example in a work environment.

00:07:56.330 --> 00:08:01.759
The next column lists the official IEEE standard
in which they are defined.

00:08:01.759 --> 00:08:05.279
You would probably never use these names when
talking with other network engineers about

00:08:05.279 --> 00:08:10.389
a cable, but you should be familiar with them.

00:08:10.389 --> 00:08:15.290
This next column lists informal standard names
given to each standard.

00:08:15.290 --> 00:08:22.759
10 base-T, 100base-T, 1000base-T, and 10gbase-t.

00:08:22.759 --> 00:08:25.650
The numbers obviously refer to their speeds.

00:08:25.650 --> 00:08:27.979
How about base and T?

00:08:27.979 --> 00:08:31.569
Well, base refers to baseband signalling.

00:08:31.569 --> 00:08:37.039
That’s totally out of the scope of the CCNA,
but just so you know the meaning.

00:08:37.039 --> 00:08:42.300
T refers to twisted pair cabling, and we’ll
talk about that very soon!.

00:08:42.300 --> 00:08:46.370
Finally, the maximum cable length.

00:08:46.370 --> 00:08:51.420
Notice that all of them are 100 meters, that’s
the maximum length for twisted pair cables

00:08:51.420 --> 00:08:55.209
as defined in Ethernet, for performance and
technical reasons.

00:08:55.209 --> 00:09:01.400
So, that’s a lot of information, but I recommend
you memorize these standards.

00:09:01.400 --> 00:09:05.399
It may seem difficult, but with the flashcards
in the description, it’s actually quite

00:09:05.399 --> 00:09:06.399
easy!

00:09:06.399 --> 00:09:10.740
So, don’t forget to download and use the
flashcards in the description, and also make

00:09:10.740 --> 00:09:11.910
your own if you want.

00:09:11.910 --> 00:09:19.000
Okay, now let’s continue and look in more
detail at the physical cables themselves.

00:09:19.000 --> 00:09:23.610
The copper cables used in Ethernet standards
are UTP cables.

00:09:23.610 --> 00:09:29.519
UTP stands for Unshielded Twisted Pair.

00:09:29.519 --> 00:09:34.250
Unshielded means that the wires have no metallic
shield, which can make them vulnerable to

00:09:34.250 --> 00:09:37.120
eletrical interference.

00:09:37.120 --> 00:09:41.280
The Twisted pair part is easy to understand
from this photo, as you can see there are

00:09:41.280 --> 00:09:44.860
four pairs of cables twisted together.

00:09:44.860 --> 00:09:49.840
The twist actually helps protect against eletromagnetic
interference, or EMI.

00:09:49.840 --> 00:09:55.540
So, there are four pairs of wires twisted
together, that makes eight wires in total.

00:09:55.540 --> 00:10:01.120
Let’s take a look at one of those RJ-45
connectors we saw earlier

00:10:01.120 --> 00:10:05.500
If you count the number of pins here, you’ll
find that there are 8 pins, perfect for the

00:10:05.500 --> 00:10:08.529
number of wires we saw in the last photo.

00:10:08.529 --> 00:10:15.020
However, not all of the Ethernet standards
we saw before actually use all 8 wires.

00:10:15.020 --> 00:10:22.180
10BASE-T and 100BASE-T, also known as Ethernet
and Fast-Ethernet cables, use 2 pairs, or

00:10:22.180 --> 00:10:24.380
4 wires.

00:10:24.380 --> 00:10:30.600
1000BASE-T and 10GBASE-T, however, use all
4 fours, or 8 wires.

00:10:30.600 --> 00:10:35.870
Let’s focus on the first two for now, 10BASE-T
and 100BASE-T.

00:10:35.870 --> 00:10:44.019
So, let’s say we’re connecting a PC to
a switch with a FastEthernet connection.

00:10:44.019 --> 00:10:49.670
These numbers represent the pins on the RJ-45
on the PCs network interface card and the

00:10:49.670 --> 00:10:52.009
switch’s interface.

00:10:52.009 --> 00:10:59.500
There are 8, but we will only use 4, or 2
pairs, since this is a fastethernet, or 100base-t,

00:10:59.500 --> 00:11:01.080
connection.

00:11:01.080 --> 00:11:04.850
The first pair is at pin positions 1 and 2,

00:11:04.850 --> 00:11:11.079
and will connect to pins at positions 1 and
2 on the switch’s network interface.

00:11:11.079 --> 00:11:16.339
Although in this diagram the wires look straight,
remember that in a UTP cable the pairs are

00:11:16.339 --> 00:11:21.350
twisted together, so in a real cable these
two wires would actually be twisted together

00:11:21.350 --> 00:11:24.240
like in the photo we saw.

00:11:24.240 --> 00:11:29.339
The PC will use pins 1 and 2 to transmit data
to the switch,

00:11:29.339 --> 00:11:32.610
which we can write as Tx.

00:11:32.610 --> 00:11:38.459
Because the PC is transmitting data on pins
1 and 2, the switch cannot transmit on those

00:11:38.459 --> 00:11:40.779
pins, it has to receive data

00:11:40.779 --> 00:11:44.699
which we can write as Rx, on pins 1 and 2.

00:11:44.699 --> 00:11:48.410
There’s an important point to remember here.

00:11:48.410 --> 00:11:55.220
The network interface card on a PC or server
transmits data on pins 1 and 2, and the interfaces

00:11:55.220 --> 00:11:59.209
on a switch receive data on pins 1 and 2.

00:11:59.209 --> 00:12:05.890
Now, the next pair that is used in a 10BASE-T
or 100-BASE-T cable is not 3 and 4.

00:12:05.890 --> 00:12:07.839
It’s 3 and 6.

00:12:07.839 --> 00:12:13.790
And, of course, the function of each pin is
opposite of the pair on pins 1 and 2.

00:12:13.790 --> 00:12:15.110
On the switch,

00:12:15.110 --> 00:12:19.860
Pins 3 and 6 are used to transmit Data, and
on the PC

00:12:19.860 --> 00:12:23.579
Pins 3 and 6 and used to receive data.

00:12:23.579 --> 00:12:28.790
This allows what’s called Full-Duplex transmission.

00:12:28.790 --> 00:12:35.110
Full-Duplex transmission means that both devices
and send data at the same time, and no problems

00:12:35.110 --> 00:12:42.069
like collisions will occur because they use
separate wires to transmit and receive data.

00:12:42.069 --> 00:12:46.540
Just like that, both devices send data at
the same time and there are no problems.

00:12:46.540 --> 00:12:52.430
Let’s change the device on the left from
a PC to a router.

00:12:52.430 --> 00:12:58.880
Just as a PC usually connects to a switch,
a switch usually connects to a router.

00:12:58.880 --> 00:13:05.160
Once again, it’s a fastethernet, or 100BASE-T
connection, so two pairs are used, 1 and 2, and

00:13:05.160 --> 00:13:06.430
3 and 6.

00:13:06.430 --> 00:13:11.860
Now, which pairs on which side are used to
transmit, and which are used to receive?

00:13:11.860 --> 00:13:16.569
Well, we know how a switch functions from
the last slide.

00:13:16.569 --> 00:13:19.269
Pins 1 and 2 receive data,

00:13:19.269 --> 00:13:22.550
and pins 3 and 6 transmit data.

00:13:22.550 --> 00:13:23.870
How about a router?

00:13:23.870 --> 00:13:29.620
Well, the network interfaces on a router transmit
and receive data on the same pairs that a

00:13:29.620 --> 00:13:32.910
PC’s network interface card does.

00:13:32.910 --> 00:13:36.370
A router transmits data on pins 1 and 2

00:13:36.370 --> 00:13:39.850
And receives data on Pins 3 and 6.

00:13:39.850 --> 00:13:43.009
Again, Ethernet uses full-duplex transmission

00:13:43.009 --> 00:13:47.990
So the two devices can send data at the same
time with no issues.

00:13:47.990 --> 00:13:55.470
So remember this, Routers transmit data on
pins 1 and 2, and receive data on pins 3 and

00:13:55.470 --> 00:13:56.470
6.

00:13:56.470 --> 00:13:59.720
This is the same as a PC.

00:13:59.720 --> 00:14:05.180
Once again, switches are the opposite, they
receive data on pins 1 and 2 and transmit

00:14:05.180 --> 00:14:08.760
data on pins 3 and 6.

00:14:08.760 --> 00:14:15.310
When connecting a PC to a switch, or a Router
to a switch, this works fine.

00:14:15.310 --> 00:14:20.500
Because they transmit and receive on opposite
pin pairs, a regular cable like this works

00:14:20.500 --> 00:14:21.900
well.

00:14:21.900 --> 00:14:26.000
This kind of cable, by the way, is called
a straight-through cable.

00:14:26.000 --> 00:14:33.490
Remember, a copper Ethernet cable has two
RJ-45 connectors, one on each end.

00:14:33.490 --> 00:14:38.759
This kind of a cable is called a ‘straight
through’ cable because pin 1 on one end

00:14:38.759 --> 00:14:41.600
connects straight through to pin 1 on the other end.

00:14:41.600 --> 00:14:47.399
Pin 2 connects to Pin 2, Pin 3 connects to
Pin 3, etc.

00:14:47.399 --> 00:14:53.410
Now, in networks we don’t always connect
PC to switch, switch to router.

00:14:53.410 --> 00:14:56.420
What if we want to connect a router to another
router?

00:14:56.420 --> 00:14:58.920
Or maybe a switch to another switch?

00:14:58.920 --> 00:15:01.180
Or maybe connect two PCs together?

00:15:01.180 --> 00:15:06.560
Now I’ve replaced the switch on the right
with another router.

00:15:06.560 --> 00:15:11.029
What will happen if the router on the left
sends data to the router on the right?

00:15:11.029 --> 00:15:15.050
Well, it’s simply not going to work.

00:15:15.050 --> 00:15:19.940
The right router isn’t prepared to receive
data on pins 1 and 2 of its interface,

00:15:19.940 --> 00:15:23.779
so communication between the two routers just
doesn’t happen.

00:15:23.779 --> 00:15:27.839
So, how can we successfully connect two routers
together?

00:15:27.839 --> 00:15:31.500
Or perhaps two switches, or two PCs.

00:15:31.500 --> 00:15:35.850
The same thing applies to connecting a PC
directly to a router, also, because they both

00:15:35.850 --> 00:15:41.010
transmit data on pins 1 and 2, and receive
data on pins 3 and 6.

00:15:41.010 --> 00:15:42.500
Let’s take a look.

00:15:42.500 --> 00:15:49.970
I’ve replaced the two routers with two switches,
just to demonstrate that the same thing applies.

00:15:49.970 --> 00:15:55.759
If the switch on the left tries to transmit
some data to the switch on the right it doesn’t

00:15:55.759 --> 00:15:56.980
work.

00:15:56.980 --> 00:16:00.810
The answer to this problem is a different
type of cable.

00:16:00.810 --> 00:16:08.570
A straight-through cable connects pin 1 to
pin 1, pin 2 to pin 2, pin 3, to pin 3, etc.

00:16:08.570 --> 00:16:13.310
But there’s another type of cable, called
a crossover cable.

00:16:13.310 --> 00:16:18.060
In a crossover cable, a pin on one end of
the cable doesn’t connect straight to the

00:16:18.060 --> 00:16:20.019
same pin on the other end.

00:16:20.019 --> 00:16:23.230
Essentially, the pairs are reversed on each
end.

00:16:23.230 --> 00:16:26.150
So, pin 1 on one side connects to

00:16:26.150 --> 00:16:28.990
Pin 3 on the other side.

00:16:28.990 --> 00:16:31.140
And pin 2 on one side connects to

00:16:31.140 --> 00:16:33.920
Pin 6 on the other side.

00:16:33.920 --> 00:16:39.459
As you can see, the two pairs, 1 and 2, and
3 and 6, are reversed.

00:16:39.459 --> 00:16:44.779
Then, pair 3 on the left side will connect
to Pin 1 on the right side.

00:16:44.779 --> 00:16:49.730
And pin 6 on the left side will connect to
pin 2 on the right side.

00:16:49.730 --> 00:16:54.540
The wires are ‘crossed over’ each other,
hence the name ‘crossover cable’.

00:16:54.540 --> 00:17:00.111
The transmit pins on one side are connected
to the receive pins on the other side, so

00:17:00.111 --> 00:17:04.720
now the two devices can send data to each
other with no problems.

00:17:04.720 --> 00:17:07.760
Here’s another example.

00:17:07.760 --> 00:17:12.900
Again, the network interface card on a PC
and the network interfaces on a router both

00:17:12.900 --> 00:17:19.450
transmit data on pins 1 and 2 and receive
data on pins 3 and 6, however if you connect

00:17:19.450 --> 00:17:25.710
them together with a crossover cable, they
will be able to exchange data with no issues.

00:17:25.710 --> 00:17:31.500
Here’s a chart reviewing different device
types and the pins they use to transmit and

00:17:31.500 --> 00:17:34.080
receive data

00:17:34.080 --> 00:17:40.950
Routers transmit data on Pins 1 and 2, and
receive data on pins 3 and 6.

00:17:40.950 --> 00:17:47.330
Firewalls are the same as routers, they transmit
data on Pins 1 and 2 and receive data on pins

00:17:47.330 --> 00:17:50.060
3 and 6.

00:17:50.060 --> 00:17:57.190
PCs also transmit data on Pins 1 and 2, and
receive data on pins 3 and 6.

00:17:57.190 --> 00:18:00.340
Switches are the only different one of the
group.

00:18:00.340 --> 00:18:06.480
Switches transmit data on pins 3 and 6, and
receive data on pins 1 and 2.

00:18:06.480 --> 00:18:08.100
Try to remember these.

00:18:08.100 --> 00:18:11.900
The flashcards included in the description
will help with this, so I recommend that you

00:18:11.900 --> 00:18:12.900
use them!

00:18:12.900 --> 00:18:19.020
While all of that is important information
to know, and can cause issues in networks

00:18:19.020 --> 00:18:24.200
even in the modern day, the truth is that
most modern networking devices have evolved

00:18:24.200 --> 00:18:28.690
beyond having to worry about straight-through
or crossover cables.

00:18:28.690 --> 00:18:35.430
That’s because newer networking devices
include a feature called Auto MDI-X.

00:18:35.430 --> 00:18:40.470
Previously, if two switches were connected
with a straight-through cable like this, they

00:18:40.470 --> 00:18:43.210
would be unable to communicate.

00:18:43.210 --> 00:18:49.820
However, Auto MDI-X allows devices to automatically
detect which pins their neighbor is transmitting

00:18:49.820 --> 00:18:55.840
data on, and then adjust which pins they use
to transmit and receive data.

00:18:55.840 --> 00:18:58.550
They can then exchange data normally.

00:18:58.550 --> 00:19:03.510
So, unless you’re working with network equipment
that is quite old, you don’t really have

00:19:03.510 --> 00:19:06.970
to worry about straight-through and crossover
cables.

00:19:06.970 --> 00:19:11.230
But this is good information to be aware of,
and it’s also good to learn about the concept

00:19:11.230 --> 00:19:16.210
of auto MDI-X, both for the exam and for real world
networking.

00:19:16.210 --> 00:19:22.890
So, we’ve talked a lot about 10BASE-T and
100BASE-T, but what about the higher speed

00:19:22.890 --> 00:19:24.920
copper ethernet cables?

00:19:24.920 --> 00:19:32.130
Remember, I said before that for gigabit ethernet
and 10 gigabit ethernet, all 8 wires are used.

00:19:32.130 --> 00:19:38.080
The last two pairs are 4 and 5, and 7 and
8.

00:19:38.080 --> 00:19:41.620
Again, there will be flashcards to help you
remember these details.

00:19:41.620 --> 00:19:46.700
It may seem like a lot to memorize, but if
you use the flashcards properly its amazing

00:19:46.700 --> 00:19:49.690
how easy it is to remember all of these things.

00:19:49.690 --> 00:19:57.900
Now, here’s another big difference between
1000baseT and 10GBASE-T, and 10base-t and

00:19:57.900 --> 00:20:00.140
100-base-t.

00:20:00.140 --> 00:20:06.890
In addition to using all four pairs of wires,
in 1000base-T and 10Gbase-T, each pair is

00:20:06.890 --> 00:20:12.790
bidirectional, meaning each pair isn’t dedicated
specifically to transmitting data or receiving

00:20:12.790 --> 00:20:14.410
data.

00:20:14.410 --> 00:20:18.100
This is part of the reason that they can operate
at much faster speeds.

00:20:18.100 --> 00:20:24.130
Okay, we’ve covered a lot about connections
using copper UTP cables.

00:20:24.130 --> 00:20:28.450
But there is a newer technology that is superior
in many ways.

00:20:28.450 --> 00:20:33.600
For example, copper UTP wiring can be used
for up to 100 meters.

00:20:33.600 --> 00:20:38.850
that’s usually plenty within a LAN, but
how about for larger networks?

00:20:38.850 --> 00:20:40.680
Look at this Cisco switch here.

00:20:40.680 --> 00:20:46.030
Here it has 24 ports for RJ45 connectors.

00:20:46.030 --> 00:20:49.970
These are the ports you would connect a copper
UTP cable to.

00:20:49.970 --> 00:20:53.320
But what about these four interfaces?

00:20:53.320 --> 00:20:56.310
Take a look at this Cisco router also.

00:20:56.310 --> 00:20:59.810
It only has four RJ45 ports.

00:20:59.810 --> 00:21:02.840
The rest of them look like those other four
ports on the switch.

00:21:02.840 --> 00:21:06.930
In these interface you insert one of these

00:21:06.930 --> 00:21:10.580
It’s called an SFP transceiver.

00:21:10.580 --> 00:21:14.970
SFP means small form-factor pluggable.

00:21:14.970 --> 00:21:20.410
So you insert one of these into the device,
but still things aren’t complete.

00:21:20.410 --> 00:21:23.950
What kind of cable connects to one of these?

00:21:23.950 --> 00:21:26.320
You connect one of these cables.

00:21:26.320 --> 00:21:28.410
This is a fiber optic cable.

00:21:28.410 --> 00:21:34.540
Rather than an electrical signal over copper
wiring, these cables send light over glass

00:21:34.540 --> 00:21:36.630
fibers.

00:21:36.630 --> 00:21:39.150
Notice that there are two connectors on each
end.

00:21:39.150 --> 00:21:43.690
That’s because you need one connector to
transmit data, and one to receive data, on

00:21:43.690 --> 00:21:46.540
each end.

00:21:46.540 --> 00:21:52.810
The copper UTP cables used separate wire pairs
within the cable to transmit and receive data.

00:21:52.810 --> 00:21:58.900
The fiber-optic cables instead use separate
cables to transmit and receive, like this.

00:21:58.900 --> 00:22:03.551
Of course, ‘transmit’ on the left connects
to ‘receive’ on the right, and ‘transmit’

00:22:03.551 --> 00:22:08.210
on the right connects to ‘receive’ on
the left.

00:22:08.210 --> 00:22:11.540
Now let’s examine the structure of the cable
itself.

00:22:11.540 --> 00:22:17.070
There are four numbered parts in this diagram,
from the center to the outer layer.

00:22:17.070 --> 00:22:20.740
Number 1 is the fiberglass core itself.

00:22:20.740 --> 00:22:26.730
Light is transmitted down this core to transmit
data from one device to another.

00:22:26.730 --> 00:22:29.760
Number 2 is cladding that reflects light,

00:22:29.760 --> 00:22:37.040
Number 3 is a protective buffer, which protects
the fiberglass from breaking

00:22:37.040 --> 00:22:40.490
and number 4 is the outer jacket of the cable.

00:22:40.490 --> 00:22:44.440
Now there are a couple main types of fiber-optic
cables.

00:22:44.440 --> 00:22:45.690
single-mode fiber, and

00:22:45.690 --> 00:22:47.140
multimode fiber.

00:22:47.140 --> 00:22:52.590
Let’s check out their characteristics and
differences.

00:22:52.590 --> 00:22:56.440
These are two examples of multimode fiber
cables.

00:22:56.440 --> 00:23:01.360
The center represents the fiberglass core,
and the blue represents the reflective cladding

00:23:01.360 --> 00:23:03.970
that reflects light down the cable.

00:23:03.970 --> 00:23:13.290
In multimode fiber cable, the core, the actual
glass fiber, is wider than single mode fiber.

00:23:13.290 --> 00:23:18.820
This wider core allows multiple angles, known
as modes, of lightwaves to enter the fiber

00:23:18.820 --> 00:23:22.580
glass core, as you can see in these two diagrams.

00:23:22.580 --> 00:23:26.050
Notice the red and black lines representing
light waves travelling down the fiberglass

00:23:26.050 --> 00:23:31.650
core, reflecting off the cladding at different
angles.

00:23:31.650 --> 00:23:37.090
Multimode fiber allows longer cables than
UTP, which are limited to 100 meters, but

00:23:37.090 --> 00:23:42.600
still shorter than single-mode fiber, which
we will look at next.

00:23:42.600 --> 00:23:47.330
Multimode fiber cables are cheaper than single-mode
fiber, and this is because they use cheaper

00:23:47.330 --> 00:23:51.790
transmitters, which are often LED-based.

00:23:51.790 --> 00:23:54.860
This is an example of a single-mode fiber
cable.

00:23:54.860 --> 00:23:59.750
Again, the center represents the fiberglass
core, and the blue represents the reflective

00:23:59.750 --> 00:24:02.030
cadding.

00:24:02.030 --> 00:24:06.990
The core diameter of a single-mode fiber cable
is narrower than a multimode fiber, meaning

00:24:06.990 --> 00:24:09.740
the glass fiber is thinner.

00:24:09.740 --> 00:24:15.350
You can notice this in the diagram here, compared
to the multimode fiber diagrams.

00:24:15.350 --> 00:24:21.160
Light enters at a single angle, known as a
mode, from a laser-based transmitter.

00:24:21.160 --> 00:24:26.950
Notice in the diagram that the light wave
travels straight down the core of the cable.

00:24:26.950 --> 00:24:32.790
Single-mode fiber allows longer cable lengths
than both UTP and multimode fiber cables.

00:24:32.790 --> 00:24:37.210
And single-mode fiber cables are more expensive
than multimode fiber cables due to the more

00:24:37.210 --> 00:24:39.810
expensive laser-based transmitters used.

00:24:39.810 --> 00:24:46.580
Okay, now let’s look at some standards for
fiber-optic cables like we did with UTP cables.

00:24:46.580 --> 00:24:51.900
Here’s another chart like the one we looked
at for copper UTP cable standards, this time

00:24:51.900 --> 00:24:55.590
for fiber-optic cables.

00:24:55.590 --> 00:25:02.240
First up is a standard for 1 gigabit ethernet
over fiber, known as 1000BASE-LX.

00:25:02.240 --> 00:25:07.220
It is defined in the IEEE 802.3zed, or zee,
standard.

00:25:07.220 --> 00:25:11.800
This standard can be used over single-mode
or multimode fiber cables, and you can see

00:25:11.800 --> 00:25:18.320
the difference in the maximum cable lengths,
550 meters for multimode fiber, and 5 kilometers,

00:25:18.320 --> 00:25:22.850
or 5000 meters, for single mode fiber.

00:25:22.850 --> 00:25:30.170
Next up is 10GBASE-SR, defined in the 802.3ae
standard, which operates at 10 gigabits per

00:25:30.170 --> 00:25:32.490
second.

00:25:32.490 --> 00:25:38.250
It uses multimode fiber and can support cable
lengths up to 400 meters.

00:25:38.250 --> 00:25:45.690
Next is 10GBASE-LR, also defined in the 802.3ae
standard, again operating at 10 gigabits per

00:25:45.690 --> 00:25:47.020
second.

00:25:47.020 --> 00:25:55.100
10GBASE-LR, however, uses single-mode fiber,
and cables lengths can be up to 10 kilometers.

00:25:55.100 --> 00:26:02.290
Finally 10GBASE-ER, also part of the 802.3ae
standard, and operating at 10 gigabits per

00:26:02.290 --> 00:26:03.800
second.

00:26:03.800 --> 00:26:09.290
It supports cable lengths even longer than
10GBASE-LR, with distances up to 30 kilometers

00:26:09.290 --> 00:26:13.260
possible over a standard connection.

00:26:13.260 --> 00:26:17.290
This is just a sample of fiber-optic standards,
there are plenty more.

00:26:17.290 --> 00:26:22.290
I will include flashcards to help you remember
these standards, but to be honest I doubt

00:26:22.290 --> 00:26:27.241
you’ll be asked questions about specific details about the
standards on the exam, but I don’t know

00:26:27.241 --> 00:26:28.860
for sure.

00:26:28.860 --> 00:26:33.190
However, with the flashcards it’s quite
easy to remember little facts like these,

00:26:33.190 --> 00:26:37.650
so I recommend not deleting those flashcards,
but that’s your choice of course.

00:26:37.650 --> 00:26:46.450
Finally, let’s review by comparing UTP cabling
and Fiber-optic cabling, starting with UTP.

00:26:46.450 --> 00:26:51.330
Copper UTP cables are cheaper than fiber-optic
cables.

00:26:51.330 --> 00:26:56.760
Maximum cables distances for UTP cables are
shorter, about 100 meters maximum.

00:26:56.760 --> 00:27:03.320
UTP cables can be vulnerable to electromagnetic
interface, or EMI, although the twist in the

00:27:03.320 --> 00:27:05.910
cable pairs helps to protect against this.

00:27:05.910 --> 00:27:12.520
The RJ45 ports to which UTP cables connect
are cheaper than the SFPs used for Fiber-optic

00:27:12.520 --> 00:27:13.520
connections

00:27:13.520 --> 00:27:21.040
Also, UTP cables emit, or leak, a faint signal
outside of the cable, which could possibly

00:27:21.040 --> 00:27:26.400
be detected and used to copy data, posing
a possible security risk.

00:27:26.400 --> 00:27:30.120
Now let’s look at fiber-optic cables.

00:27:30.120 --> 00:27:32.170
Fiber-optic cables are more expensive than
UTP cables

00:27:32.170 --> 00:27:37.390
They support longer distances than UTP cables.

00:27:37.390 --> 00:27:43.200
Their SFP ports are more expensive than RJ45
ports, and single-mode fiber ports are more

00:27:43.200 --> 00:27:45.020
expensive than multimode.

00:27:45.020 --> 00:27:51.810
They do not emit any signal outisde of the
cable, so there is no security risk there.

00:27:51.810 --> 00:27:57.360
Okay, so we covered a lot of information,
but I want to remind you of the supplementary

00:27:57.360 --> 00:28:02.290
materials for the video that will help you
remember what you learned.

00:28:02.290 --> 00:28:08.250
Like in the last video, there will be an end-of-video
quiz starting from the next slide.

00:28:08.250 --> 00:28:14.080
Also, I have made a deck of flashcards to help you
review the information covered in this video,

00:28:14.080 --> 00:28:17.960
check the link in the description to download
them.

00:28:17.960 --> 00:28:22.220
And there will also be a practice lab using
Packet Tracer, which will be released as a

00:28:22.220 --> 00:28:23.290
separate video.

00:28:23.290 --> 00:28:27.630
Okay, let’s get started with the quiz.

00:28:27.630 --> 00:28:29.670
Quiz question 1.

00:28:29.670 --> 00:28:34.900
You connect two old routers together with
a UTP cable, however data is not successfully

00:28:34.900 --> 00:28:36.900
sent and received between them.

00:28:36.900 --> 00:28:39.710
What could be the problem?

00:28:39.710 --> 00:28:43.620
A, they are connected with a straight-through
cable.

00:28:43.620 --> 00:28:48.000
B, they are connected with a crossover cable.

00:28:48.000 --> 00:28:52.880
or C, they are operating in auto MDI-x mode.

00:28:52.880 --> 00:28:58.460
Pause the video to think about your answer.

00:28:58.460 --> 00:29:02.760
The answer is A, they are connected with a
straight-through cable.

00:29:02.760 --> 00:29:07.460
let’s check each of the possible answers.

00:29:07.460 --> 00:29:10.400
A crossover cable is not the issue.

00:29:10.400 --> 00:29:14.100
In fact, a crossover cable would likely fix the issue.

00:29:14.100 --> 00:29:18.980
Because both routers transmit data on pins
1 and 2, a crossover cable is necessary to

00:29:18.980 --> 00:29:23.320
properly connect the transmit pins on one
side to the receive pins

00:29:23.320 --> 00:29:26.810
(3 and 6) on the other side.

00:29:26.810 --> 00:29:31.840
Modern devices with Auto MDI-X enabled don’t
have this issue, but it is possible that the

00:29:31.840 --> 00:29:34.100
old routers do not have Auto MDI-X.

00:29:34.100 --> 00:29:39.870
So, b, they are connected with a crossover
cable, is incorrect.

00:29:39.870 --> 00:29:44.760
Auto MDI-X allows devices to detect which
pins and wires their neighbors are using to

00:29:44.760 --> 00:29:49.720
transmit and receive data, and adjust their
own operations to match.

00:29:49.720 --> 00:29:55.250
Actually, Auto MDI-X would likely fix this
issue, but since the routers are old they

00:29:55.250 --> 00:29:57.790
might not have the Auto MDI-X function.

00:29:57.790 --> 00:30:04.500
So, c, They are operating in Auto MDI-X mode,
is incorrect.

00:30:04.500 --> 00:30:09.780
On old devices without Auto MDI-X, a straight-through
cable cannot be used to connect devices of

00:30:09.780 --> 00:30:11.230
the same type.

00:30:11.230 --> 00:30:13.940
A crossover cable is necessary.

00:30:13.940 --> 00:30:22.700
So a, they are connected with a straight-through
cable, is the best answer.    Quiz question 2.

00:30:22.700 --> 00:30:27.270
Your company wants to connect switches in
two separate buildings that are about 150

00:30:27.270 --> 00:30:29.360
meters apart.

00:30:29.360 --> 00:30:32.360
They want to keep costs down, if possible.

00:30:32.360 --> 00:30:34.650
What kind of cable should they use?

00:30:34.650 --> 00:30:37.370
A, UTP.

00:30:37.370 --> 00:30:43.440
B, Single-mode fiber, or C, multimode fiber.

00:30:43.440 --> 00:30:49.730
Pause the video to think about your answer.

00:30:49.730 --> 00:30:52.800
The answer is C, multimode fiber.

00:30:52.800 --> 00:30:55.789
Let’s check.

00:30:55.789 --> 00:31:01.470
Although UTP would keep the costs down, it
does not support distances over 100 meters.

00:31:01.470 --> 00:31:06.110
So A, UTP, is incorrect.

00:31:06.110 --> 00:31:11.900
Although single-mode fiber supports distances
much longer than 150 meters, it is more expensive

00:31:11.900 --> 00:31:13.790
than multimode fiber.

00:31:13.790 --> 00:31:19.760
So b, single-mode fiber, is not the best answer.

00:31:19.760 --> 00:31:25.070
Multimode fiber supports distances over 150
meters and is less expensive than single-mode

00:31:25.070 --> 00:31:26.110
fiber.

00:31:26.110 --> 00:31:29.380
So C, multimode fiber, is the best answer.

00:31:29.380 --> 00:31:33.320
Let’s go on to question 3.

00:31:33.320 --> 00:31:38.150
Your company wants to connect two offices
that are about 3 kilometers apart.

00:31:38.150 --> 00:31:41.120
They want to keep costs down if possible.

00:31:41.120 --> 00:31:43.510
Which kind of cable should they use?

00:31:43.510 --> 00:31:52.670
A, UTP, B, single-mode fiber, or C, multimode
fiber.

00:31:52.670 --> 00:31:59.170
Pause the video to think about your answer.

00:31:59.170 --> 00:32:01.780
The answer is b, single-mode fiber.

00:32:01.780 --> 00:32:05.120
Let’s check the answers.

00:32:05.120 --> 00:32:10.510
Although UTP keeps costs down, it does not
support distances of 3 kilometers.

00:32:10.510 --> 00:32:14.660
So A, UTP, is incorrect.

00:32:14.660 --> 00:32:20.530
Although multimode fiber is cheaper than single-mode
fiber, it also does not support distances of 3

00:32:20.530 --> 00:32:21.530
kilometers.

00:32:21.530 --> 00:32:26.430
So c, multimode fiber, is incorrect.

00:32:26.430 --> 00:32:32.190
Many single-mode fiber standards support cable
lengths much longer than 3 kilometers.

00:32:32.190 --> 00:32:36.420
Although single-mode fiber is more expensive
than the other options, it is necessary in

00:32:36.420 --> 00:32:37.890
this case.

00:32:37.890 --> 00:32:43.480
So B, multi-mode fiber, is the best answer.

00:32:43.480 --> 00:32:48.610
A switch has the following indication over
its network interfaces: What would happen

00:32:48.610 --> 00:32:52.830
if you connect it to an identical switch with
a straight-through cable?

00:32:52.830 --> 00:32:56.360
A, they would operate normally.

00:32:56.360 --> 00:33:00.940
B, they would operate at a reduced speed.

00:33:00.940 --> 00:33:05.070
or C, they would be unable to communicate.

00:33:05.070 --> 00:33:11.440
Pause the video to think about your answer.

00:33:11.440 --> 00:33:14.230
The answer is a, they would operate normally.

00:33:14.230 --> 00:33:16.860
Let’s check.

00:33:16.860 --> 00:33:19.620
They would not operate at a reduced speed.

00:33:19.620 --> 00:33:22.500
The ports are Auto MDI-X enabled.

00:33:22.500 --> 00:33:27.850
However, even if they didn’t have Auto MDI-X,
they wouldn’t operate at a reduced speed.

00:33:27.850 --> 00:33:30.660
They simply wouldn’t operate.

00:33:30.660 --> 00:33:36.470
So b, they would operate at a reduced speed,
is incorrect.

00:33:36.470 --> 00:33:41.240
Because the ports are Auto MDI-X enabled,
they would be able to communicate, even though

00:33:41.240 --> 00:33:43.830
they are connected with a straight-through
cable.

00:33:43.830 --> 00:33:49.790
So c, they would be unable to communicate,
is incorrect.

00:33:49.790 --> 00:33:54.630
Because the ports are Auto MDI-X enabled,
they would operate normally, regardless of

00:33:54.630 --> 00:33:58.910
whether they are connected with a straight-through
or a crossover cable.

00:33:58.910 --> 00:34:02.830
So a, they would operate normally, is the
correct answer.

00:34:02.830 --> 00:34:07.900
Let’s go to the final quiz question for
this video.

00:34:07.900 --> 00:34:12.399
Your company needs to connect many end hosts
to a switch which is in a wiring cabinet on

00:34:12.399 --> 00:34:15.620
the same office floor as the hosts.

00:34:15.620 --> 00:34:20.869
What kind of cable should they use? a, UTP.

00:34:20.869 --> 00:34:26.909
b, single-mode fiber, or C, multimode fiber.

00:34:26.909 --> 00:34:32.990
Pause the video to think about your answer.

00:34:32.990 --> 00:34:35.109
The answer is a, UTP.

00:34:35.109 --> 00:34:38.800
Let’s check the answers.

00:34:38.800 --> 00:34:44.000
Most hosts do not have the capability to connect
to a switch via fiber cabling, and most switches

00:34:44.000 --> 00:34:48.190
do not have enough SFP interfaces to support
many hosts.

00:34:48.190 --> 00:34:53.839
So b, single-mode fiber, and c, multimode
fiber, are inorrect.

00:34:53.839 --> 00:34:59.480
UTP cables are the standard for wired connections
to switches.

00:34:59.480 --> 00:35:04.720
Switches typically have many RJ45 ports for
end hosts to connect to, and end hosts will

00:35:04.720 --> 00:35:10.930
have an RJ45 port on their network interface
card to connect a UTP cable to.

00:35:10.930 --> 00:35:15.099
So a, UTP, is the correct answer.

00:35:15.099 --> 00:35:18.309
Thank you for watching.

